Paid Notice: Memorials  MCCARREN, J. REILLY. THE DIRECTORS AND EMPLOYEES OF THE ARKANSAS & MISSOURI RAILROAD MOURN THE LOSS OF THEIR DISTINGUISHED CHAIRMAN, CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER, CLOSE COLLEAGUE AND FRIEND, J. REILLY MCCARREN. REILLY PASSED AWAY APRIL 26 AT THE AGE OF 58. HE WAS AN ACCOMPLISHED RAILROADER AND DEDICATED LEADER WHO SPENT HIS ENTIRE PROFESSIONAL CAREER IN OUR INDUSTRY. A GRADUATE OF THE MASSACHUSETTS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY WITH A BACHELOR OF SCIENCE DEGREE AND A MASTER OF SCIENCE DEGREE IN CIVIL ENGINEERING, REILLY BEGAN HIS RAILROAD CAREER WITH CONRAIL IN 1978. HE ADVANCED TO PRESIDENT OF THE GATEWAY WESTERN RAILWAY, AND LATER PRESIDENT AND CEO OF WISCONSIN CENTRAL LTD.'S NORTH AMERICAN OPERATIONS. IN 2002, HE ACQUIRED THE MAJORITY INTEREST IN THE A&M AND ITS AFFILIATED COMPANY, ALLIED ENTERPRISES, INC. HE WORKED TIRELESSLY OVER THE LAST 13 YEARS TO BRING THESE COMPANIES TO THE FIRST RANK OF THE REGIONAL RAILROAD INDUSTRY. THESE ACCOMPLISHMENTS HAVE BEEN RECOGNIZED THROUGH A SERIES OF NATIONAL AWARDS. WE EXTEND OUR HEARTFELT CONDOLENCES TO HIS WIFE, CAREN, THEIR CHILDREN, CHRISTOPHER AND KATHLEEN, REILLY'S MOTHER, JUDITH, AND HIS BROTHERS, GERARD AND MARK. WE HAVE LOST AN ESTEEMED COLLEAGUE WHO ALWAYS DEMONSTRATED DEEP LOVE FOR OUR INDUSTRY AND OUR COMPANY, WITH ITS COMMITMENT TO NORTHWEST ARKANSAS. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  WHITNEY, C. SEARLE. BORN NOVEMBER 14,1944, DIED MARCH 27, 2015 TO PARENTS CORNELIUS V. WHITNEY AND ELEANOR SEARLE WHITNEY MCCOLLUM. SEARLE GREW UP IN HIS TENDER YEARS IN OLD WESTBURY, NEW YORK. HIS MOST JOYOUS TIMES WERE THE YEARS IN THE DIFFERENT SEASONS IN THE ADIRONDACKS. IT BROUGHT HIM, AT AN EARLY AGE IN TOUCH WITH NATURE. IT BECAME A PART OF HIM FOR HIS 70 YEARS OF LIFE. HE GAVE BACK THIS JOY. HE GRADUATED FROM CHOATE, YALE PHD AND THEN TO HARVARD WHERE HE WAS CHOSEN TO WORK ON A UNIQUE PROGRAM, WHICH WAS QUITE A SECRET IN COMPUTER PSYCHOLOGY. WE, TODAY ARE EXPOSED TO THAT UNUSUAL WORK IN A CURRENT FILM "THE IMMITATION GAME". LEAVING HARVARD, CHANGED THE COURSE OF HIS LIFE. HE WENT WEST LANDING IN BERKELEY, CALIFORNIA WITH THE ADIRONDACK SOIL STILL ALIVE IN HIM AND UNDER HIS THUMB NAILS, HE BEGAN TO CREATE BEAUTIFUL UNTRADITIONAL GARDENS. ANOTHER PASSION WAS MUSIC. CHOPIN IN THE EARLY YEARS. HE MARRIED SARAH CROSS IN THE LATE 80'S AND HAD A SON HARRY C. WHITNEY. THE MARRIAGE WAS SHORT LIVED, BUT SEARLE PASSED BOTH HIS PASSION FOR MUSIC AND THE GREAT OUTDOORS TO HARRY. SEARLE WHITNEY WAS AN ECONOMIST, PSYCHOLOGIST AND A PHILANTHROPIST. HE WAS VERY CONCERNED ABOUT THE EFFECTS OF A GROWING HUMAN POPULATION ON OUR COMMUNITIES AND THE ENVIRONMENT. IN 2006 HE STARTED THE INSTITUTE FOR THE POPULATION STUDIES TO RAISE AWARENESS FOR POPULATION GROWTH. ACCORDING TO SEARLE AND WHAT BECAME THE ORGANIZATION'S MISSION STATEMENT "WE CAN HELP SOLVE ALL THIS BY INCREASING ACCESS TO LOW COST CONTRACEPTION, SUPPORTING WOMEN'S RIGHTS, AND INCREASING ENVIRONMENTAL AWARENESS. WITH THESE TOOLS, PEOPLE EVERYWHERE CAN DETERMINE THE BEST POPULATION SIZE FOR THEIR FAMILY, THEIR REGION AND THE WORLD." SEARLE FOUGHT A LONG TWO YEARS BATTLE OF HODGKINS LYMPHOMA. IN HIS ENDING, AT HOME WITH HOSPICE CARE HE HAD HIS OLD TIME MUSIC PARTNER, LAURA LIND WHO WAS ALSO HIS SIGNIFICANT OTHER. HIS BELOVED SON, HARRY C. WHITNEY WAS BY HIS SIDE. THERE WAS A CELEBRATION OF SEARLE WHITNEY, AN EXTRAORDINARY MAN, AT ALL SAINTS EPISCOPAL CHURCH ON SATURDAY, MAY 9, 2015. IN BERKELEY. HIS WONDERFUL TRUE BLUE FRIENDS WERE ALL THERE TO CELEBRATE HIM AND THEIR MUSIC. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  ROSENBLOOM, IRVING RICHARD, "DICK" PASSED AWAY WEDNESDAY, MAY 13 FOLLOWING A COURAGEOUS BATTLE WITH PANCREATIC CANCER. HE LEAVES HIS WIFE BERNIS; WITH WHOM HE SHARED MANY HAPPY YEARS AND WHO HAD GIVEN HIM SUCH LOVING CARE. HE IS ALSO SURVIVED BY HIS DAUGHTER AMY, SON DAVID, GRANDCHILDREN ALISON, MICHAEL AND DYLAN, SISTER ERNA AND BROTHERS ARTHUR, GERRY AND DAN. DICK WAS BORN IN NEW YORK ON JUNE 28, 1925 TO SOL ROSENBLOOM AND FRIEDA VOGEL. HE SPENT SPENT MOST OF HIS EARLY YEARS IN BELLE HARBOR, LONG ISLAND AND IN 1939 MOVED WITH THE FAMILY TO RICHMOND, VA WHERE HE GRADUATED FROM JOHN MARSHALL HIGH SCHOOL. WITH THE WAR ON, AND HAVING BARELY ATTAINED THE AGE OF 18, HE ENROLLED IN THE UNITED STATES ARMY AIR CORP'S AIR CADET PROGRAM FROM WHICH HE WAS COMMISSIONED A SECOND LIEUTENANT AND ASSIGNED TO DUTY ON A B29 SUPERFORTRESS BOMBER. AFTER THE WAR, DICK JOINED AND SERVED FOR MANY YEARS WITH THE FAMILY'S RICHMOND BASED WHOLESALE APPAREL BUSINESS. AFTER RETIRING IN FLORIDA, HE DECIDED TO RETURN TO WORK ESTABLISHING RICHARD ROSENBLOOM ASSOCIATES PROVIDING MERCHANDISING AND MARKETING SERVICES TO A WIDE ARRAY OF INDEPENDENT RETAILERS WHICH HE SUCCESSFULLY HEADED UNTIL THE PAST YEAR. DICK WAS EXTREMELY CLOSE AND LOYAL TO ALL HIS FAMILY. STRIKINGLY HANDSOME, UNUSUALLY CHARMING AND ENERGETIC HIS WARM PRESENCE WAS HIGHLY VALUED. MOST IMPORTANTLY, HE WAS RECEPTIVE TO THE COMMENTS AND THOUGHTS OF HIS MANY FRIENDS AND SINCERELY HOPEFUL FOR THEIR WELL BEING. HE WILL BE SORELY MISSED. SERVICES AT 12 NOON, MONDAY, MAY 18 AT QUATTLEBAUM FUNERAL HOME, 5411 OKEECHOBEE BOULEVARD, WEST PALM BEACH, FL 33417. SHIVA FROM 4PM, TUESDAY, MAY 19 ONLY AT AMY'S HOME. TELEPHONE 212, 674, 5990. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  ROSENBLOOM, IRVING RICHARD, "DICK" PASSED AWAY WEDNESDAY, MAY 13 FOLLOWING A COURAGEOUS BATTLE WITH PANCREATIC CANCER. HE LEAVES HIS WIFE BERNIS; WITH WHOM HE SHARED MANY HAPPY YEARS AND WHO HAD GIVEN HIM SUCH LOVING CARE. HE IS ALSO SURVIVED BY HIS DAUGHTER AMY, SON DAVID, GRANDCHILDREN ALISON, MICHAEL AND DYLAN, SISTER ERNA AND BROTHERS ARTHUR, GERRY AND DAN. DICK WAS BORN IN NEW YORK ON JUNE 28, 1925 TO SOL ROSENBLOOM AND FRIEDA VOGEL. HE SPENT SPENT MOST OF HIS EARLY YEARS IN BELLE HARBOR, LONG ISLAND AND IN 1939 MOVED WITH THE FAMILY TO RICHMOND, VA WHERE HE GRADUATED FROM JOHN MARSHALL HIGH SCHOOL. WITH THE WAR ON, AND HAVING BARELY ATTAINED THE AGE OF 18, HE ENROLLED IN THE UNITED STATES ARMY AIR CORP'S AIR CADET PROGRAM FROM WHICH HE WAS COMMISSIONED A SECOND LIEUTENANT AND ASSIGNED TO DUTY ON A B29 SUPERFORTRESS BOMBER. AFTER THE WAR, DICK JOINED AND SERVED FOR MANY YEARS WITH THE FAMILY'S RICHMOND BASED WHOLESALE APPAREL BUSINESS. AFTER RETIRING IN FLORIDA, HE DECIDED TO RETURN TO WORK ESTABLISHING RICHARD ROSENBLOOM ASSOCIATES PROVIDING MERCHANDISING AND MARKETING SERVICES TO A WIDE ARRAY OF INDEPENDENT RETAILERS WHICH HE SUCCESSFULLY HEADED UNTIL THE PAST YEAR. DICK WAS EXTREMELY CLOSE AND LOYAL TO ALL HIS FAMILY. STRIKINGLY HANDSOME, UNUSUALLY CHARMING AND ENERGETIC HIS WARM PRESENCE WAS HIGHLY VALUED. MOST IMPORTANTLY, HE WAS RECEPTIVE TO THE COMMENTS AND THOUGHTS OF HIS MANY FRIENDS AND SINCERELY HOPEFUL FOR THEIR WELL BEING. HE WILL BE SORELY MISSED. SERVICES AT 12 NOON, MONDAY, MAY 18 AT QUATTLEBAUM FUNERAL HOME, 5411 OKEECHOBEE BOULEVARD, WEST PALM BEACH, FL 33417. SHIVA FROM 4PM, TUESDAY, MAY 19 ONLY AT AMY'S HOME. TELEPHONE 212, 674, 5990. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  SCHIMMEL, GERTRUDE (NEE TANNENBAUM) DIED PEACEFULLY ON MONDAY, MAY 11TH, AT HER HOME IN MANHATTAN. WIDOW OF ALFRED SCHIMMEL. LOVING MOTHER OF EDWARD AND THE LATE VICTOR SCHIMMEL. DEVOTED SISTER OF FRANCES WEINSTEIN, AND THE LATE HAROLD TANNENBAUM. PROUD GRANDMOTHER OF DIANA, GREGORY, AMELIA AND JOANNA. MOTHER, IN, LAW OF SYDNEY FIRESTONE SCHIMMEL AND MARLENE SCHIMMEL. BELOVED AUNT OF MARK WEINSTEIN (ESTHER), IRA TANNENBAUM (LUCRETIA), JUDITH TANNENBAUM, FLORENCE WESS (ANDREW) AND ROZ SHUSTAK (MARK). GERTRUDE WAS A LIFE, LONG RESIDENT OF NEW YORK CITY, WHICH SHE PROUDLY SERVED FOR 41 YEARS IN THE NYPD, AND A MEMBER OF THE SHOMRIM SOCIETY. SHE GRADUATED FROM MORRIS HIGH SCHOOL AND PHI BETA KAPPA FROM HUNTER COLLEGE. SHE ENJOYED TENNIS, BRIDGE AND POKER, WHICH SHE PLAYED IN TOURNAMENTS IN LAS VEGAS AND ATLANTIC CITY WELL INTO HER 90S. A MEMORIAL SERVICE WILL BE HELD ON WEDNESDAY, MAY 20TH AT 4PM AT TEMPLE EMANU, EL, 1 EAST 65TH STREET IN MANHATTAN. IN LIEU OF FLOWERS, DONATIONS MAY BE MADE TO MACULAR DEGENERATION RESEARCH, 22512 GATEWAY CENTER DRIVE, CLARKSBURG, MD 20871. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  MARTIN, HOWARD CURTISS, 62, DIED UNEXPECTEDLY, BUT PEACEFULLY, AT THE FAMILY HOME IN BROOKSVILLE, ME ON APRIL 30TH. CURTISS ATTENDED THE ST. BERNARD'S, BROOKS, AND RIVERDALE COUNTRY SCHOOLS. HE STUDIED ECONOMICS AND HISTORY AT TUFTS UNIVERSITY AND WORKED AS AN ECONOMIST FOR THE CONGRESSIONAL RESEARCH SERVICE OF THE LIBRARY OF CONGRESS. HE EARNED HIS J.D. FROM THE UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA SCHOOL OF LAW, WHERE HE WAS A CO, FOUNDING EDITOR OF THE VIRGINIA TAX REVIEW. CURTISS PRACTICED TAX LAW IN NEW YORK WITH WEBSTER & SHEFFIELD AND PAUL, WEISS BEFORE JOINING MOBIL CORPORATION IN NEW YORK AND THEN FAIRFAX, VA, WHERE HIS AREAS OF EXPERTISE INCLUDED FEDERAL AND INTERNATIONAL CORPORATE TAXATION, TAX PLANNING, AND STRUCTURING COMPLEX TRANSACTIONS, WORK HE CONTINUED IN HOUSTON, TX FOR EXXONMOBIL AFTER THE MOBIL MERGER. BEFORE HIS RECENT RETIREMENT, CURTISS SERVED AS DIRECTOR, WASHINGTON NATIONAL TAX FOR KPMG. CURTISS WAS BORN IN NEW YORK TO THE LATE LEE G. AND GEORGINA G. MARTIN. HE IS SURVIVED BY HIS WIFE VIRGINIA W. DREWRY AND THEIR DAUGHTER ABIGAIL T. M. MARTIN, BOTH OF ALEXANDRIA, VA AND BROOKSVILLE; HIS SISTERS ELEANOR T. M. HOAGLAND (LEIGH W. HOAGLAND) AND M. KATE MARTIN (JOHN C. SHIMROCK) OF NEW YORK, AND MARY ARCHER MARTIN OF GARRISON NY; HIS NEPHEW AND NIECE NICHOLAS G. HOAGLAND AND GEORGINA G. HOAGLAND OF NEW YORK; AND A HOST OF FRIENDS. PLEASE TAKE A MOMENT TO WRITE DOWN AND SHARE YOUR MEMORIES OF CURTISS WITH HIS FAMILY AND FRIENDS. IF YOU WISH, YOU MAY ALSO HONOR HIS MEMORY BY CONTRIBUTING TO A PROJECT OR PASSION OF YOUR CHOOSING; THE BLUE HILL PUBLIC LIBRARY, 5 PARKER POINT ROAD, BLUE HILL ME 04614; OR THE ISLAND INSTITUTE, 386 MAIN STREET, ROCKLAND ME 04841. SERVICES WILL BE HELD IN MAINE IN AUGUST. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  ROCKEFELLER, MARGARETTA "HAPPY" OUR BELOVED MOTHER, MARGARETTA "HAPPY" FITLER ROCKEFELLER, PEACEFULLY PASSED AWAY IN HER SLEEP ON THE MORNING OF TUESDAY, MAY 19. HER CHILDREN AND MANY LOVED ONES GATHERED AROUND HER IN LOVING MEMORY. WE ARE BLESSED THAT UP UNTIL HER DEATH, SHE WAS HAPPILY ACTIVE AND ENGAGED WITH HER FAMILY, BELOVED FRIENDS AND INTERESTS. THROUGHOUT HER LIFE, OUR MOTHER WAS A CONSTANT INSPIRATION AND SOURCE OF PROFOUND LOVE AND WISDOM FOR HER FAMILY AND FRIENDS. OUR MOTHER CARED DEEPLY ABOUT HER FAMILY, FRIENDS, AND THE WELL BEING OF OTHERS. DURING WORLD WAR II, SHE SERVED IN THE AMERICAN WOMEN'S VOLUNTEER SERVICE AND ALSO SERVED AS A NURSE'S AIDE IN THE PHILADELPHIA NAVAL HOSPITAL ASSISTING THE WOUNDED. SHE HAD A KEEN INTEREST IN UNDERSTANDING AND SPENDING TIME WITH DIFFERENT PEOPLES AND CULTURES. SHE WORKED QUIETLY TO PROMOTE MUTUAL UNDERSTANDING AND HAD AN UNCANNY ABILITY TO GENERATE UNDERSTANDING AND RESPECT AMONG PEOPLE OF DIFFERENT BACKGROUNDS AND VIEWS. AS FIRST LADY OF NEW YORK AND SECOND LADY OF THE UNITED STATES AND AS A CONCERNED AND INTERESTED CITIZEN, SHE VISITED ALL PARTS OF THE GLOBE. SHE WAS APPOINTED TO TWO TERMS AS A PUBLIC DELEGATE TO THE UNITED NATIONS BY PRESIDENT GEORGE H. W. BUSH IN 1991 AND 1992, SERVING UNDER US AMBASSADOR THOMAS PICKERING. AFTER HER SERVICE, SHE CONTINUED TO ADVANCE HER COUNTRY'S INTERESTS THERE AND HOST IMPORTANT GATHERINGS. SHE HAD A DEEP LOVE OF LEARNING AND READ THROUGHOUT HER LIFE HISTORICAL NOVELS AND HISTORY. SHE WAS PROUD OF HOW HER HERITAGE AND HER FAMILY HAD HELPED AMERICA OVER THE YEARS. HER GREAT, GREAT, GRANDFATHER, GENERAL GEORGE MEADE, WAS COMMANDER OF THE UNION ARMY AT THE BATTLE OF GETTYSBURG. SHE WAS THE GREAT GRANDDAUGHTER OF EDWIN H. FITLER, FORMER MAYOR OF PHILADELPHIA. AND SHE WAS ALSO DESCENDED FROM JONATHAN DICKENSON, THE FOUNDER OF PRINCETON UNIVERSITY, AND JOSEPH HARRISON, WHO BUILT THE RAILROADS IN RUSSIA UNDER TSAR NICHOLAS II. AS A BREAST CANCER SURVIVOR ENDURING TWO MASTECTOMIES SHORTLY AFTER HER HUSBAND NELSON ROCKEFELLER BECAME VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES, SHE PLAYED AN IMPORTANT ROLE, ALONG WITH FIRST LADY BETTY FORD, IN HELPING PEOPLE GAIN A GREATER AWARENESS OF BREAST CANCER AND ITS DETECTION. HER CHARITABLE INTERESTS INCLUDED HEARTFELT SUPPORT FOR THE PHILADELPHIA ORCHESTRA AND ITS ANNUAL VISITS TO CHINA AND THE ORCHESTRA'S MISSION OF PROMOTING INTERNATIONAL UNDERSTANDING. SHE SUPPORTED THE FRANKLIN D. ROOSEVELT FOUR FREEDOMS PARK IN NEW YORK CITY, THE CENTRAL PARK CONSERVANCY, THE ROCKEFELLER STATE PARK PRESERVE, AND SERVED ON THE BOARD OF HISTORIC HUDSON VALLEY AND AS A TRUSTEE OF THE ROCKEFELLER BROTHERS FUND. SHE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD OF THE SARATOGA PERFORMING ARTS CENTER (SPAC) FROM ITS FORMATION IN 1966 UNTIL 1973 AND WAS NAMED AS HONORARY CHAIRPERSON FOR SPAC'S 50TH ANNIVERSARY CELEBRATION IN 2016. AS A MOTHER SHE GUIDED US WITH HER STEADFAST LOVE AND THOUGHTFUL INSIGHTS AND UNDERSTANDING OF PEOPLE AND THE WORLD. SHE TAUGHT US THE VALUE AND IMPORTANCE OF FRIENDS AND FAMILY AND COUNTRY. SHE SHARED WITH US HER DEEP LOVE OF NATURE FROM WHICH SHE DREW STRENGTH AND SPIRITUALITY. SHE DELIGHTED IN FEEDING BIRDS AND WILDLIFE NEAR HER HOME. FOR OVER THIRTY FIVE YEARS SHE WAS A DEDICATED SWIMMER NEARLY EVERY DAY. SHE DEEPLY ENJOYED TAKING LONG WALKS WITH LOVED ONES AS OFTEN AS SHE COULD. MOM WAS A KIND AND GIVING WOMAN, WHO LEFT US WITH LOVING MEMORIES THAT WILL REMAIN FOREVER. OUR MOTHER, ABOVE ALL, WAS DEDICATED TO HER IMMEDIATE AND EXTENDED FAMILY AND TO MANY DEAR FRIENDS. SHE GREATLY LOVED SPENDING TIME WITH HER CHILDREN, INCLUDING MALINDA MENOTTI WHO PASSED AWAY IN 2005, AND FOURTEEN GRANDCHILDREN. SHE HAD A FIRM BELIEF IN THE IMPORTANCE OF FAMILY AND THE NURTURING, SUPPORT, AND PERSPECTIVE IT PROVIDES. ON TUESDAY, JUNE 9 THERE WILL BE A PRIVATE FUNERAL WITH FAMILY AND CLOSE FRIENDS. IN SEPTEMBER THERE WILL BE A MEMORIAL CELEBRATION OF HER LIFE. WE GREATLY MISS HER AND WE WILL ALWAYS BE GUIDED BY HER WISDOM AND LOVE. THE CHILDREN OF MRS. NELSON A. "HAPPY" ROCKEFELLER; JAMES B. MURPHY, WENDY M. BICKFORD, CAROL M. LYDEN, NELSON A. ROCKEFELLER, JR., MARK F. ROCKEFELLER. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  ROCKEFELLER, MARGARETTA "HAPPY" OUR BELOVED MOTHER, MARGARETTA "HAPPY" FITLER ROCKEFELLER, PEACEFULLY PASSED AWAY IN HER SLEEP ON THE MORNING OF TUESDAY, MAY 19. HER CHILDREN AND MANY LOVED ONES GATHERED AROUND HER IN LOVING MEMORY. WE ARE BLESSED THAT UP UNTIL HER DEATH, SHE WAS HAPPILY ACTIVE AND ENGAGED WITH HER FAMILY, BELOVED FRIENDS AND INTERESTS. THROUGHOUT HER LIFE, OUR MOTHER WAS A CONSTANT INSPIRATION AND SOURCE OF PROFOUND LOVE AND WISDOM FOR HER FAMILY AND FRIENDS. OUR MOTHER CARED DEEPLY ABOUT HER FAMILY, FRIENDS, AND THE WELL BEING OF OTHERS. DURING WORLD WAR II, SHE SERVED IN THE AMERICAN WOMEN'S VOLUNTEER SERVICE AND ALSO SERVED AS A NURSE'S AIDE IN THE PHILADELPHIA NAVAL HOSPITAL ASSISTING THE WOUNDED. SHE HAD A KEEN INTEREST IN UNDERSTANDING AND SPENDING TIME WITH DIFFERENT PEOPLES AND CULTURES. SHE WORKED QUIETLY TO PROMOTE MUTUAL UNDERSTANDING AND HAD AN UNCANNY ABILITY TO GENERATE UNDERSTANDING AND RESPECT AMONG PEOPLE OF DIFFERENT BACKGROUNDS AND VIEWS. AS FIRST LADY OF NEW YORK AND SECOND LADY OF THE UNITED STATES AND AS A CONCERNED AND INTERESTED CITIZEN, SHE VISITED ALL PARTS OF THE GLOBE. SHE WAS APPOINTED TO TWO TERMS AS A PUBLIC DELEGATE TO THE UNITED NATIONS BY PRESIDENT GEORGE H. W. BUSH IN 1991 AND 1992, SERVING UNDER US AMBASSADOR THOMAS PICKERING. AFTER HER SERVICE, SHE CONTINUED TO ADVANCE HER COUNTRY'S INTERESTS THERE AND HOST IMPORTANT GATHERINGS. SHE HAD A DEEP LOVE OF LEARNING AND READ THROUGHOUT HER LIFE HISTORICAL NOVELS AND HISTORY. SHE WAS PROUD OF HOW HER HERITAGE AND HER FAMILY HAD HELPED AMERICA OVER THE YEARS. HER GREAT, GREAT, GRANDFATHER, GENERAL GEORGE MEADE, WAS COMMANDER OF THE UNION ARMY AT THE BATTLE OF GETTYSBURG. SHE WAS THE GREAT GRANDDAUGHTER OF EDWIN H. FITLER, FORMER MAYOR OF PHILADELPHIA. AND SHE WAS ALSO DESCENDED FROM JONATHAN DICKENSON, THE FOUNDER OF PRINCETON UNIVERSITY, AND JOSEPH HARRISON, WHO BUILT THE RAILROADS IN RUSSIA UNDER TSAR NICHOLAS II. AS A BREAST CANCER SURVIVOR ENDURING TWO MASTECTOMIES SHORTLY AFTER HER HUSBAND NELSON ROCKEFELLER BECAME VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES, SHE PLAYED AN IMPORTANT ROLE, ALONG WITH FIRST LADY BETTY FORD, IN HELPING PEOPLE GAIN A GREATER AWARENESS OF BREAST CANCER AND ITS DETECTION. HER CHARITABLE INTERESTS INCLUDED HEARTFELT SUPPORT FOR THE PHILADELPHIA ORCHESTRA AND ITS ANNUAL VISITS TO CHINA AND THE ORCHESTRA'S MISSION OF PROMOTING INTERNATIONAL UNDERSTANDING. SHE SUPPORTED THE FRANKLIN D. ROOSEVELT FOUR FREEDOMS PARK IN NEW YORK CITY, THE CENTRAL PARK CONSERVANCY, THE ROCKEFELLER STATE PARK PRESERVE, AND SERVED ON THE BOARD OF HISTORIC HUDSON VALLEY AND AS A TRUSTEE OF THE ROCKEFELLER BROTHERS FUND. SHE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD OF THE SARATOGA PERFORMING ARTS CENTER (SPAC) FROM ITS FORMATION IN 1966 UNTIL 1973 AND WAS NAMED AS HONORARY CHAIRPERSON FOR SPAC'S 50TH ANNIVERSARY CELEBRATION IN 2016. AS A MOTHER SHE GUIDED US WITH HER STEADFAST LOVE AND THOUGHTFUL INSIGHTS AND UNDERSTANDING OF PEOPLE AND THE WORLD. SHE TAUGHT US THE VALUE AND IMPORTANCE OF FRIENDS AND FAMILY AND COUNTRY. SHE SHARED WITH US HER DEEP LOVE OF NATURE FROM WHICH SHE DREW STRENGTH AND SPIRITUALITY. SHE DELIGHTED IN FEEDING BIRDS AND WILDLIFE NEAR HER HOME. FOR OVER THIRTY FIVE YEARS SHE WAS A DEDICATED SWIMMER NEARLY EVERY DAY. SHE DEEPLY ENJOYED TAKING LONG WALKS WITH LOVED ONES AS OFTEN AS SHE COULD. MOM WAS A KIND AND GIVING WOMAN, WHO LEFT US WITH LOVING MEMORIES THAT WILL REMAIN FOREVER. OUR MOTHER, ABOVE ALL, WAS DEDICATED TO HER IMMEDIATE AND EXTENDED FAMILY AND TO MANY DEAR FRIENDS. SHE GREATLY LOVED SPENDING TIME WITH HER CHILDREN, INCLUDING MALINDA MENOTTI WHO PASSED AWAY IN 2005, AND FOURTEEN GRANDCHILDREN. SHE HAD A FIRM BELIEF IN THE IMPORTANCE OF FAMILY AND THE NURTURING, SUPPORT, AND PERSPECTIVE IT PROVIDES. ON TUESDAY, JUNE 9 THERE WILL BE A PRIVATE FUNERAL WITH FAMILY AND CLOSE FRIENDS. IN SEPTEMBER THERE WILL BE A MEMORIAL CELEBRATION OF HER LIFE. WE GREATLY MISS HER AND WE WILL ALWAYS BE GUIDED BY HER WISDOM AND LOVE. THE CHILDREN OF MRS. NELSON A. "HAPPY" ROCKEFELLER; JAMES B. MURPHY, WENDY M. BICKFORD, CAROL M. LYDEN, NELSON A. ROCKEFELLER, JR., MARK F. ROCKEFELLER. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  GILBERT, S. PARKER. THE TRUSTEES AND STAFF OF THE METROPOLITAN MUSEUM OF ART MOURN DEEPLY THE PASSING OF PARKER GILBERT, A DEVOTED LEADER AND FRIEND OF THE MUSEUM, AND ONE OF THE MOST ACTIVE AND INFLUENTIAL TRUSTEES IN ITS HISTORY. HE SHARED HIS ADVICE AND BROAD EXPERTISE OVER MANY YEARS AS A TRUSTEE (1990, 2010), TRUSTEE EMERITUS (2010, 15), AND VICE CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD (1999, 2010). HIS INVOLVEMENT ALSO EXTENDED TO CHAIRING THE MET'S NOMINATING AND INVESTMENT COMMITTEES, AND SERVING ACTIVELY AS A MEMBER OF ITS EXECUTIVE, COMPENSATION, FINANCE, BUDGET, ACQUISITIONS, EMPLOYEE BENEFITS, AND INSTITUTIONAL RESPONSIBILITY COMMITTEES, AS WELL AS THE VISITING COMMITTEE FOR THE DEPARTMENT OF MODERN AND CONTEMPORARY ART. WITH HIS WIFE GAIL, HE MADE GENEROUS CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE MUSEUM, INCLUDING A LANDMARK GIFT IN 2000 ESTABLISHING AN ENDOWMENT FUND THAT PROVIDES VITAL SUPPORT FOR A RANGE OF EXHIBITIONS. PARKER WAS A CALM, AUTHORITATIVE, AND REASSURING LEADER, PARTICULARLY DURING TIMES OF FISCAL STRAIN, AND HE WAS ALWAYS ABLE TO LOOK BEYOND THE HORIZON TO DEFINE AND CONTINUE TO BUILD A HEALTHIER MUSEUM. HE WAS A MENTOR TO STAFF AND FELLOW TRUSTEES, AND ALSO CONTRIBUTED GENEROUSLY IN THE TRADITION OF HIS FAMILY, THE MORGANS. ALWAYS HIGH, MINDED AND DETERMINED, WHILE DEEPLY HUMAN AND PHILANTHROPIC, HE WAS AN EXTRAORDINARY COLLEAGUE WHOM WE WILL MISS GREATLY. WE EXTEND OUR HEARTFELT CONDOLENCES TO GAIL AND TO THE ENTIRE FAMILY. DANIEL BRODSKY, CHAIRMAN THOMAS P. CAMPBELL, DIRECTOR AND CEO EMILY K. RAFFERTY, PRESIDENT EMERITA 1
